===Etymology===
Attested since the 1830s in American English, a jocular mock-Latin word.<ref name=quinion>{{R:World Wide Words|entry=Absquatulate|url=weirdwords/ww-abs1|date_created=3 August 2002}}</ref> {{blend|en|abscond|squat|perambulate}}, as {{m|en|ab-||away (from)}} (as in {{m|en|abscond}}) + {{m|en|squat}} + {{m|en|*-ulate}} (as in {{m|en|perambulate}}, properly {{m|en|-ate}}), hence meaning “get up (from a squat) and depart (quickly)”.<ref name=quinion/><ref>New Orleans ''Weekly Picayune,'' December 1839</ref> The middle portion was perhaps influenced by {{m|en|-le||(frequentative)}} and the dialectal term {{m|en|squattle||depart}}; compare contemporary {{m|en|skedaddle}}.

